    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="174"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d174">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.21/299.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minister <persName type="from">Thomson</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation, <lb/> Bogotá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 29, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>On assuming office the Concho administration has been confronted with a deficit
                    of $3,000,000 and has found an empty treasury which there is at present but
                    little prospect of replenishing, owing to the effects of the European war and
                    the attendant trade stagnation. * * *</p>
                <p>If the treaty can be ratified, with an amendment to pay the indemnity by
                    installments (which I feel would now be accepted although I have received no
                    official intimation in that sense) the effect throughout Colombia would be
                    especially felicitous at this juncture. * * *</p>
                <p>It is important for the Legation to know what are the prospects for ratification
                    and whether consideration will be put off until the next session of
                    Congress.</p>
                <p>The present session of the Colombian Congress will come to a close next October
                    20. Congress will not convene again until July, 1915. If therefore, the treaty
                    is to be amended by the Senate, it is most desirable that action be taken now
                    and not postponed until December. * * *</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Thomson</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
